article.description: Kristin Folkl scored her only basket with  36.7 seconds left to break a tie and give the Portland Fire their franchise-record fifth straight victory, 76-73 over the Charlotte Sting on Wednesday night.
article.headline: Fire win despite blowing 18-point lead
article.linkText: Folkl makes her only points count in Fire's fifth straight win
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Kristin Folkl scored her only basket with  36.7 seconds left to break a tie and give the Portland Fire their franchise-record fifth straight victory, 76-73 over the Charlotte Sting on Wednesday night.

	   "I guess two points isn't a whole lot, but it came at a real
critical time,'' Folkl said. "We are very happy with how we are
playing right now, especially on a tough road trip like this.''

	   DeMya Walker had 18 points and 11 rebounds, and Sylvia Crawley
added 15 points and blocked Dawn Staley's 3-point attempt with 3
seconds left for the Fire (9-8), who won despite blowing an
18-point second-half lead.

	   Allison Feaster scored 17 points and Staley added 14 for the
Sting (7-7), who lost at home for the first time in seven games
this season.

	   The loss also snapped a 13-game regular-season home winning
streak dating to last season, tied for third-best in WNBA history.

	   Tammy Sutton-Brown had 13 points and 10 rebounds for Charlotte,
but she missed a layup with 17 seconds left that would have tied
it.

	   "I thought there was contact, but the refs weren't calling it
all night,'' Sutton-Brown said. "I'm disappointed I didn't make
the shot.''

	   The Sting used a 16-2 run to get back in it. Sutton-Brown's
fast-break layup with 10:14 left cut the deficit to 57-55.
Charlotte tied it for the first time on Feaster's 3-pointer with
3:22 to play.

	   "The second 20 minutes -- that's the team I want to coach,''
Sting coach Anne Donovan said. "We need to bring that more than 20
minutes to win.''

	   Walker's bucket in the first minute of the second half gave
Portland its largest lead at 50-32.

	   The Fire, who shot 6-of-7 from 3-point range and made all six of
their free throws, never trailed and shot 58 percent from the field
-- including 75 percent (18-of-24) in the first half. The teams
combined to make 17-of-27 3-pointers.

"Never have we shot the ball like that,'' Portland coach Linda
Hargrove said. "It was really fun to see and I hope I can see
something like that again.''
